%N A334991 a(n) = 4^n + 3 * 18^n.
%C A334991 This sequence is a variation of the sequence A333385, variation proposed by Tony Gardiner in his book in reference.
%C A334991 Proposition: a(n) is a perfect square iff n = 0; in this case, a(0) = 4.
%D A334991 A. Gardiner, The Mathematical Olympiad Handbook: An Introduction to Problem Solving, Oxford University Press, 1997, reprinted 2011, page 115 (1991).
%H A334991 <a href="/index/Rec#order_02">Index entries for linear recurrences with constant coefficients</a>, signature (22,-72).
%F A334991 a(n) = A000302(n) + 3 * A001027(n).
%F A334991 a(n) = 22*a(n-1) - 72*a(n-2) for n>1.
%F A334991 G.f.: (4 - 30*x)/((1 - 4*x)*(1 - 18*x)). - _Alejandro J. Becerra Jr._, Jun 01 2020
%e A334991 a(4) = 4^4 + 3 * 18^4 = 315184 = 2^4 * 19699 is not a perfect square.
%p A334991 S:=seq(4^n+3*18^n, n=0..20);
